<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOME IMPROVEMENT; 
</P>
<P>
GET EDGE ON QUALITY IN BUILDING WITH PLYWOOD; 
</P>
<P>
FINISH: THERE ARE SEVERAL WAYS TO DISPLAY WORKMANSHIP MAKING THE ROUGH EDGES OF 
BOARDS LOOK SMOOTH. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LARRY EISINGER, Eisinger, author of How to Build and Contract Your Own Home, 
is a do-it-yourself authority and syndicated columnist. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If you're building a piece of furniture, ripping some shelving from a sheet of 
plywood or fabricating a countertop for plastic laminate or ceramic tile, the 
way you finish the edges will reflect the quality of your workmanship. 
</P>
<P>
Plywood got its name because thin layers, or plies, of wood were glued together 
at right angles to each other, which provided stability and rigidity, in a 
manufacturing process that yielded more usable wood from each log. However, the 
process also resulted in a panel with a rough edge. Chipboard -- made by mixing 
and compressing small chips of wood in an adhesive -- also has a rough edge 
that requires special treatment. 
</P>
<P>
You have many edge-finishing options that you can exercise, depending on the 
project, your skill and your tools. 
</P>
<P>
A very popular way to conceal the end grain is to miter the corners, as 
illustrated in Figure 1. However, this requires a table or radial arm saw, 
absolutely flat material and some skill on your part. 
</P>
<P>
Probably the mostly widely used edge treatment -- because it's easier and more 
economical -- is to fill the edge grain with a paste wood filler, sand the 
filler smooth and repeat the application until the grain no longer is visible, 
as illustrated in Figure 2. 
</P>
<P>
Another technique that is faster but slightly more expensive is to glue and 
nail decorative molding to the front (see Figure 3). This is an especially fine 
technique when making a coffee table or decorative shelving. 
</P>
<P>
If you are working with expensive hardwood panels, such as birch or mahogany, 
and plan to show the natural grain and color of the wood, your edge treatment 
should be to adhere a strip of the same type wood to the edge, as shown in 
Figure 4. A contact adhesive is best, and the veneer should be at least 
one-eighth inch wider than the thickness of the plywood. When in place, the 
protruding edge of the veneer can be easily cut away with a plane, razor or 
even sanded so it is flush with the top. 
</P>
<P>
If you are building a kitchen countertop or making shelves that require 
additional reinforcement, the edge treatment illustrated in Figure 5 is best. 
Screw and nail straight white pine pieces, sand smooth and you are ready for 
covering the surface and edge with ceramic tile or the most widely used 
countertop material, decorative plastic laminate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Chart, PLYWOOD EDGE FINISHING / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA112590-0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 312953 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 25, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
