<HEADLINE>
<P>
OUTTAKES: QUITE A TIP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By From Kirk Honeycutt 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Last Tuesday novelist Chris Moore was waiting tables in a Cambria restaurant. 
Then word reached him that Disney's Hollywood Pictures won a bidding war and 
purchased film rights to Moore's unpublished novel, "Practical Demon Keeping," 
a black comedy about a man and his monster, for producer Laurence Marks. 
</P>
<P>
A Disney source confirmed that the package, which includes producer Jennifer 
Levine, went for more than $1 million. From Kirk Honeycutt 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA112590-0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 313041 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 25, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 58; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
136 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALLA BREVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TIMOTHY MANGAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BACH: The Well-Tempered Clavier. Joao Carlos Martins, piano. Tomato 2699132. 
Martins focuses the listener's attention not on Bach's music, but on his own 
manner of playing it. 
</P>
<P>
He uses a whole range of rhetorical devices for expressive purposes, everything 
from unwritten rubatos and accents to gratuitous colorings and fussy 
articulations. Though occasionally he offers a straightforward reading by way 
of contrast, he often backs off even further, draining the music of all 
inflection and emotion and turning innocent counterpoint into stark 
mathematical formula. In giving many of these pieces a strongly pianistic and 
melodic cast, he obscures their multiple-voiced complexities. Martins's 
noodling may rarely bore, but it does seem arbitrary, and what Bach wrote is 
vastly more interesting. TIMOTHY MANGAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Recording Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
