<P>
FIRE SPRINKLER STANDARDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The City Council has agreed to meet soon with business owners and the Chamber 
of Commerce to study a proposal for tougher city fire sprinkler standards. 
</P>
<P>
Currently, places of public assembly, such as restaurants and theaters, must be 
outfitted with sprinklers if they are 5,000 square feet or larger. Other 
businesses must install sprinklers if they are 10,000 square feet in size. 
</P>
<P>
Fire Chief Mark Foote recommended Tuesday that sprinklers be required for 
buildings half as big -- 2,500 square feet for places of public assembly and 
5,000 square feet for other businesses. 
</P>
<P>
Foote stopped short of urging that sprinklers be required for homes and 
apartments, saying smoke detectors and non-combustible roofs do an adequate job 
of preventing fires there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
